# Simulated SNMP device for the OAT SNMP live-signal demo.
#
# snmpsim maps the SNMP community string to the .snmprec basename, so this file is served for
# community "public" — matching the connector default (OAT_SNMP_COMMUNITY, packages/
# connectors/src/snmp.ts). It answers exactly the OIDs the OAT SNMP connector GETs:
#
#   1.3.6.1.2.1.1.1.0            sysDescr           device description   (identity)
#   1.3.6.1.2.1.1.3.0            sysUpTime          time since boot      (liveness)
#   1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0            sysName            device name          (identity)
#   1.3.6.1.2.1.43.10.2.1.4.1.1  prtMarkerLifeCount lifetime page count  (THE work signal)
#
# The record format is:  <OID>|<type-tag>[:<variation-module>]|<value-or-params>
# Type tags: 4 = OctetString, 65 = Counter32, 67 = TimeTicks.
#
# sysUpTime and prtMarkerLifeCount use snmpsim's `numeric` variation module, which returns a
# non-decreasing integer that grows with time (rate = units per second). That is the whole
# point of the demo: two reads a few seconds apart return DIFFERENT page counts, and that
# delta is the only real evidence a printer did work. A printer answering an SNMP walk is
# reachable, not busy (ADR-0008) — a moving prtMarkerLifeCount is busy. The connector turns
# the increase into a `utilisation busy:true` signal; a flat counter would be a heartbeat.
1.3.6.1.2.1.1.1.0|4|Lablink OAT Demo Printer (snmpsim) - Brother TD-4550
1.3.6.1.2.1.1.3.0|67:numeric|rate=100,initial=0
1.3.6.1.2.1.1.5.0|4|oat-demo-printer
1.3.6.1.2.1.43.10.2.1.4.1.1|65:numeric|rate=10,initial=1000
